#X text 42 19 Internally we have [allpass.filt~] \, which stacks 2nd order allpass filters. The input is summed to the filter output and the 'wet' input controls the mix. At full wet they're summed together and we have notches where the phase cancelation points are. You can set the number of stages with the 1st argument or 'n' message. A 'Q' value lets you set the 'Q' for the 2nd order filters. This is not a common parameter for phasers \, which are usually built with stacked 1st order allpass filters without a Q setting. A 'Q' value of 0.5 (the default) is equivalent to stacking 1st order filters. Higher values bring the notches closer to the center frequency \, while lower values take them appart. The frequency LFO needs to come form an external source., f 67;
